description: From Middle English umbesetten (“to surround”), from Old English ymbsettan (“to set around, surround, beset, encompass”), from Proto-Germanic *umbi (“around”) + *satjaną (“to set”); equivalent to um- +‎ beset or umbe- +‎ set. Compare also Old English ymbsittan (“to sit around, surround”), Dutch omzetten (“to convert, transpose”), German umsetzen (“to move to another place, convert, transform, transplant, adjust, rearrange”). More at umbe, set.

verbs.description: umbeset (third-person singular simple present umbesets, present participle umbesetting, simple past umbeset, past participle umbeset or umbesetten)

entries.meaning: (obsolete or dialectal, chiefly Scotland) To block, obstruct; act detrimentally toward.
examples: […] , and pressing to have bereft them of their lives by umbesetting of the high gates to that effect at divers times of before,  […]

entries.meaning: (obsolete or dialectal, chiefly Scotland) To overwhelm; cover completely.
